    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Segment Adjusted EBITDA: Definition, Construction, and Segment Calculations\n\n## 1. Definition\n\nThe filing defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as:\n\n> **Segment income (loss) from operations** excluding (i) depreciation and amortization, (ii) share-based compensation, (iii) restructuring charges, and (iv) impairment.\n\nThe most directly comparable GAAP measure is **segment income (loss) from operations**. Management uses Segment Adjusted EBITDA as a key performance measure to assess financial performance and for internal planning and forecasting.\n\nThe filing also defines the consolidated **Adjusted EBITDA** (starting from net income/loss) as excluding eight items: depreciation and amortization, share-based compensation, impairment, restructuring charges, interest expense, interest income, other (income) expense net, and provision for income taxes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Adjustments Made to GAAP Figures\n\n### For Segment Adjusted EBITDA (starting from segment income/loss from operations):\n\n| # | Adjustment | Direction |\n|---|-----------|-----------|\n| 1 | Depreciation and amortization | Added back |\n| 2 | Share-based compensation | Added back |\n| 3 | Restructuring charges | Added back |\n| 4 | Impairment | Added back |\n\n### For consolidated Adjusted EBITDA (starting from net income/loss), four additional items are also excluded:\n\n| # | Additional Adjustment | Direction |\n|---|----------------------|-----------|\n| 5 | Interest expense | Added back |\n| 6 | Interest income | Deducted |\n| 7 | Other (income) expense, net | Added back |\n| 8 | Provision for (benefit from) income taxes | Added back |\n\nThe filing cautions that these non-GAAP measures should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for GAAP measures, and that other companies may calculate them differently.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Segment-Level Calculation — Three Months Ended March 31, 2026\n\n> **Important note on segment naming:** The user\'s question references "Launch, Starlink, xAI, X." The filing actually reports **three** reportable segments — **Space**, **Connectivity**, and **AI** — not four. The mapping is:\n> - "Launch" → **Space** segment\n> - "Starlink" → **Connectivity** segment\n> - "xAI" → **AI** segment\n> - "X" → **Not a separate segment.** The filing references the Twitter-to-X rebranding only in the context of a 2023 impairment charge ($3,775 million) recorded within the AI segment. There is no standalone X segment in the reconciliation tables.\n\n### Space Segment (in millions)\n\n| Line Item | Amount |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Income (loss) from operations (GAAP) | $(662) |\n| Add: Depreciation and amortization | 166 |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | 145 |\n| Add: Restructuring charges | — |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$(351)** |\n\nThe Space segment\'s Adjusted EBITDA turned negative in Q1 2026 (down $575 million from $224 million in Q1 2025), primarily driven by accelerated investment in Starship vehicle development and launch facilities.\n\n### Connectivity Segment (Starlink) (in millions)\n\n| Line Item | Amount |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Income (loss) from operations (GAAP) | $1,188 |\n| Add: Depreciation and amortization | 783 |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | 116 |\n| Add: Restructuring charges | — |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$2,087** |\n\nThe Connectivity segment is the strongest performer, driven by Starlink subscriber growth (10.3 million subscribers in Q1 2026 vs. 5.0 million in Q1 2025), increasing enterprise adoption, and supply chain efficiencies in user terminal production.\n\n### AI Segment (xAI) (in millions)\n\n| Line Item | Amount |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Income (loss) from operations (GAAP) | $(2,469) |\n| Add: Depreciation and amortization | 1,493 |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | 378 |\n| Add: Restructuring charges | (11) |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$(609)** |\n\nThe AI segment (formed from the xAI acquisition in February 2026) is in a heavy investment phase. The operating loss increased $1,533 million year-over-year, driven by higher cloud computing and GPU depreciation costs, data center infrastructure, and employee expenses. The filing notes a multi-year investment horizon is expected before sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA is achieved.\n\n### Total Reportable Segments (in millions)\n\n| Line Item | Amount |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Income (loss) from operations (GAAP) | $(1,943) |\n| Add: Depreciation and amortization | 2,442 |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | 639 |\n| Add: Restructuring charges | (11) |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$1,127** |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Consolidated Reconciliation — Q1 2026 (for reference)\n\nThe total Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $1,127 million ties to the consolidated Adjusted EBITDA, which is reconciled from net income as follows (in millions):\n\n| Line Item | Amount |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Net income (loss) | $(4,276) |\n| Depreciation and amortization | 2,442 |\n| Share-based compensation | 639 |\n| Restructuring charges | (11) |\n| Impairments | — |\n| Interest expense | 664 |\n| Interest income | (213) |\n| Other (income) expense, net | 1,876 |\n| Provision for (benefit from) income taxes | 6 |\n| **Adjusted EBITDA** | **$1,127** |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Historical Context — Notable Segment Trends\n\n| Period | Space Adj. EBITDA | Connectivity Adj. EBITDA | AI Adj. EBITDA | Total |\n|--------|-------------------|--------------------------|----------------|-------|\n| Q1 2026 | $(351) | $2,087 | $(609) | $1,127 |\n| Q1 2025 | $224 | $1,618 | $(112) | $1,730 |\n| FY 2025 | $653 | $7,168 | $(1,237) | $6,584 |\n| FY 2024 | $1,154 | $3,849 | $347 | $5,350 |\n| FY 2023 | $997 | $1,602 | $1,222 | $3,821 |\n\nKey observations:\n- **Space** has declined as Starship R&D investment accelerates (from $997M in 2023 to $(351)M in Q1 2026).\n- **Connectivity** has grown dramatically (from $1,602M in 2023 to $7,168M in 2025), driven by Starlink scale and efficiency.\n- **AI** was profitable in 2023–2024 (including a $3,775M impairment reversal benefit in 2023 related to the Twitter/X brand), but turned negative in 2025–2026 as compute infrastructure investment scaled rapidly.\n- The **X/Twitter rebranding impairment** of $3,775 million in 2023 was recorded within the AI segment, not as a separate X segment.',
