        output='Based on the provided filing chunks, here is the disclosure, presentation, and breakdown of capital expenditures (capex) by segment, along with notable presentation conventions.\n\n### What the Filing Discloses\nThe filing discloses capital expenditures across three reportable segments—**Space**, **Connectivity**, and **AI**—for the years ended December 31, 2023, 2024, and 2025, as well as the three months ended March 31, 2025 and 2026. \n\nThe disclosures detail the strategic drivers for the capex increases in each segment:\n*   **Space:** Increases are primarily driven by increased investment in launch site infrastructure for Starship.\n*   **Connectivity:** Increases are driven by higher satellite and ground equipment costs to increase the number of satellites and grow the Starlink network.\n*   **AI:** The massive ramp in capex is driven by investments in the rapid expansion of terrestrial data centers, including the development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure.\n\n### How Capex is Presented\nCapex is presented in two distinct ways throughout the filing:\n1.  **Standalone MD&A and Preamble Tables:** A dedicated table presents "Capital expenditures by segment" across multiple periods. \n2.  **Segment Reporting Notes:** Capex is included as a line item under "Supplemental segment information" at the bottom of the segment financial tables, alongside other non-GAAP/supplemental metrics like depreciation and amortization, share-based compensation, and impairments.\n\n### Capex Amounts by Segment\nThe standalone tables provide the following capex amounts (in millions):\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 (3 mos.) | Q1 2025 (3 mos.) | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Space** | $1,052 | $759 | $3,832 | $2,032 | $1,497 |\n| **Connectivity** | $1,332 | $814 | $4,178 | $3,498 | $2,455 |\n| **AI** | $7,723 | $2,567 | $12,727 | $5,633 | $463 |\n| **Total Capital Expenditures** | **$10,107** | **$4,140** | **$20,737** | **$11,163** | **$4,415** |\n\n*(Note: The FY 2023, FY 2024, FY 2025, Q1 2025, and Q1 2026 segment notes reconcile exactly to the standalone table above.)*\n\n### Unusual Presentation Conventions\nThere are a few unusual or notable presentation conventions regarding capex and the segment tables in this filing:\n\n1.  **Mixed Periodicity in a Single Table:** The standalone capex table in the MD&A and Preamble combines quarters and full years into a single contiguous row of columns. It jumps from "Three Months Ended March 31, 2026" directly into "Three Months Ended March 31, 2025," and then into "Year Ended December 31, 2025, 2024, 2023." Mixing quarterly and annual data side-by-side in one table without a clear visual break is atypical for financial filings.\n2.  **Negative Restructuring Charges:** In the Q1 2026 segment table, "Restructuring charges" for the AI segment (and thus the Total Reportable Segments) are presented as a negative number: **$(11)**. Expenses are typically presented as positive numbers that are summed up to reach total costs. Presenting an expense as a negative figure effectively makes it a credit that reduces total costs and expenses.\n3.  **Capitalized Interest Inclusion:** While not explicitly shown in the capex line item, the notes disclose that the company capitalizes interest during the construction of significant long-term projects, such as AI infrastructure data centers and launch facilities (e.g., $169 million in 2025 and $7 million in Q1 2026). This capitalized interest is bundled into Construction-in-progress within Property, plant, and equipment, meaning the segment capex figures implicitly include capitalized interest rather than presenting it separately.',
