    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Subscriber and Usage Metrics Disclosed in the Filing\n\n## 1. Starlink Subscribers\n\n### Definition\nA **Starlink Subscriber** is defined as a unique **Service Line** directly assigned to a Starlink.com account registered to a person or entity that does **not** have a direct, negotiated agreement with the Starlink sales team. A Service Line is an individual instance of Starlink broadband internet service provisioned under a subscription plan, generally associated with a specific terminal or group of terminals.\n\n### Scope and Inclusions\n- **Included:** Personal plans (Residential, Roam) and Business plans (Local Priority, Global Priority).\n- **Excluded:** Managed enterprise and government customers with contracts in aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, and government entities.\n- **Calculation:** Number of unique Service Lines at the **end of the period**.\n\n### Reported Counts\n\n| Period | Starlink Subscribers (millions) | YoY Growth |\n|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 (three months ended March 31, 2026) | 10.3 | 105% |\n| Q1 2025 (three months ended March 31, 2025) | 5.0 | 91% |\n| FY 2025 | 8.9 | — |\n| FY 2024 | 4.4 | — |\n| FY 2023 | 2.3 | — |\n\nThe filing notes these subscribers span **164 countries, territories, and other markets** as of March 31, 2026.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Starlink Subscriber ARPU\n\n### Definition\n**ARPU** is calculated as:\n\n> Service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers during the period ÷ [(i) average number of Starlink Subscribers during the period × (ii) number of months in the period]\n\nThis yields a **monthly** ARPU figure.\n\n### Reported Values\n\n| Period | Monthly ARPU |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $66 |\n| Q1 2025 | $86 |\n| FY 2025 | $81 |\n| FY 2024 | $91 |\n| FY 2023 | $99 |\n\n### Strategic Context and Expected Trajectory\nThe filing explicitly states the company\'s strategy is **focused on scale over ARPU**:\n\n> "Our strategy is focused on driving sustainable revenue growth and expanding our margins through operational efficiencies and technological advancements, rather than prioritizing increases in ARPU."\n\nThe company **expects ARPU to continue declining** due to:\n- Growth of the subscriber base outside North America\n- Addition of lower-priced service plans\n- Adjustments to monthly service plan fees for broadband offerings\n\nHowever, it expects these dynamics to be **offset by increased scale** and technological advancement in launch, satellite, and user terminal operations.\n\n### Revenue Decomposition Context\nThe MD&A quantifies the interplay between subscriber growth and ARPU decline:\n\n- **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:** Consumer revenue growth composed of **104.7% growth in Starlink Subscribers**, offset by a **22.9% decline in ARPU**.\n- **FY 2025 vs. FY 2024:** Consumer revenue growth composed of **99.9% growth in Starlink Subscribers**, offset by an **11.2% decline in ARPU**.\n- **FY 2024 vs. FY 2023:** Consumer revenue growth composed of **96.5% growth in Starlink Subscribers**, offset by an **8.1% decline in ARPU**.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Nameplate Compute Draw (AI Infrastructure Metric)\n\n### Definition\n**Nameplate Compute Draw** = (Number of GPUs installed in data centers at end of period) × (respective all-in power draw per GPU).\n\n### Critical Definitional Caveats\n- Reflects **installed capacity**, **not** actual power consumption or utilization.\n- **Excludes** power for supporting infrastructure: cooling systems, power distribution losses, lighting, security systems, and facility-level overhead.\n\n### Reported Values\n\n| Period | Nameplate Compute Draw (gigawatts) |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | 1.0 |\n| Q1 2025 | 0.3 |\n| FY 2025 | 0.8 |\n| FY 2024 | 0.3 |\n| FY 2023 | 0 |\n\nThe increase to 1.0 GW as of March 31, 2026 is attributed to bringing **COLOSSUS and COLOSSUS II** online.\n\n---\n\n## 4. AI Usage and Platform Metrics\n\nThe filing discloses **limited granular AI usage metrics**. Notably, it does **not** disclose token consumption, API call volumes, or similar transactional AI metrics. Instead, it reports platform-level user metrics:\n\n### X and Grok Integrated AI Platforms (as of March 31, 2026)\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Supported accounts active in trailing twelve months | Over 1.3 billion |\n| Monthly Active Users (MAUs) | ~550 million |\n| Daily posts generated | ~350 million |\n| MAUs that used Grok\'s AI features | ~117 million |\n\n### AI Segment Revenue Sources\nThe filing identifies three AI revenue streams but does not break out usage volume per stream:\n1. **Premium subscriptions** on X and Grok (recognized ratably over subscription term, ranging from month-to-month to one year)\n2. **Data licensing** arrangements (recognized ratably, from month-to-month to two years)\n3. **API** services\n\nThe MD&A notes that AI segment revenue increased by **$91 million** in Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 "from higher X and Grok subscriptions," and by **$581 million** in FY 2025 vs. FY 2024 "as advertising, Grok and X subscriptions, and data licensing arrangements grew."\n\n### Starlink Mobile (Satellite-to-Mobile) Metrics\n\n| Metric | Value (as of March 31, 2026) |\n|---|---|\n| Monthly unique devices | ~7.4 million |\n| Countries served | ~30 |\n| Dedicated V1 Mobile satellites | ~650 |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Comparability Issues\n\n### Starlink Subscribers\n1. **Service Line vs. individual user mismatch:** The metric counts Service Lines, not people. Multiple individuals in a household may share one Service Line, meaning actual end users are "likely meaningfully higher than 10.3 million." Conversely, a single entity may hold multiple Service Lines (e.g., Residential + Roam), inflating the count relative to unique customers.\n2. **Exclusion of enterprise/government:** Managed enterprise and government customers (aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, government entities) are excluded, meaning the metric **understates total Starlink reach** and is not comparable to competitors who may include such customers in subscriber counts.\n3. **No device-level granularity:** The count does not distinguish between terminals, account holders, or physical persons, making comparison to metrics like "connections" or "customers" used by telecom competitors imprecise.\n4. **Rapid geographic mix shift:** As the base grows internationally, the composition of subscribers changes, affecting any per-subscriber comparisons across periods.\n\n### Starlink Subscriber ARPU\n1. **Declining by design:** ARPU has fallen from $99 (FY 2023) to $66 (Q1 2026), driven by international expansion and lower-priced plans. Period-over-period comparisons are inherently confounded by this mix shift.\n2. **Revenue scope limitation:** ARPU is calculated only on service revenue from Starlink Subscribers as defined (excluding enterprise/government), so it does **not** reflect blended connectivity revenue per user across the entire customer base.\n3. **Average subscriber base:** The denominator uses the **average** number of subscribers during the period, which smooths rapid growth. In periods of high sequential growth, this average may understate the ending subscriber base significantly, potentially inflating ARPU relative to a point-in-time calculation.\n4. **No hardware revenue inclusion:** ARPU reflects only service revenue, not Starlink Kit (terminal) hardware sales, limiting its comparability to total revenue per user metrics used by some competitors.\n\n### Nameplate Compute Draw\n1. **Capacity, not utilization:** The metric measures installed nameplate capacity, not actual power draw or GPU utilization. Two companies with identical Nameplate Compute Draw could have vastly different actual compute output.\n2. **Excludes overhead:** Cooling, power distribution, lighting, and facility overhead are excluded, meaning total facility power requirements are significantly higher than the metric suggests. Comparisons to total data center power metrics used by other operators would not be apples-to-apples.\n3. **GPU mix opacity:** The metric aggregates across GPU types by multiplying count × respective power draw, but the filing does not disclose the specific GPU mix, making it difficult to infer actual compute capability (e.g., FLOPS).\n\n### AI Platform Metrics\n1. **"Supported accounts" vs. MAUs ambiguity:** The 1.3 billion figure refers to "supported accounts active in the last twelve months," which is a broader and less standardized measure than MAUs (~550 million). The relationship between these two figures is not fully defined.\n2. **Grok AI users as a subset:** The 117 million MAUs who "used Grok\'s AI features" is a subset of the 550 million total MAUs, but the definition of "used" (e.g., passive exposure vs. active engagement) is not specified.\n3. **No transactional AI metrics:** The filing does not disclose token consumption, API call volume, inference requests, or training compute hours—metrics that would be more directly comparable to AI infrastructure usage at peers. This limits comparability to companies like OpenAI or Anthropic that may report such figures.\n4. **Conflation of X and Grok:** The AI segment bundles advertising (X platform), subscriptions (X and Grok), and data licensing, making it difficult to isolate pure AI product usage from social platform engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table of All Disclosed Metrics\n\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Starlink Subscribers (M) | 10.3 | 5.0 | 8.9 | 4.4 | 2.3 |\n| Starlink ARPU ($/month) | $66 | $86 | $81 | $91 | $99 |\n| Nameplate Compute Draw (GW) | 1.0 | 0.3 | 0.8 | 0.3 | 0 |\n| X+Grok supported accounts (B, TTM) | 1.3+ | — | — | — | — |\n| X+Grok MAUs (M) | ~550 | — | — | — | — |\n| Grok AI feature MAUs (M) | ~117 | — | — | — | — |\n| Starlink Mobile monthly unique devices (M) | ~7.4 | — | — | — | — |',
        error=None,
