        args='{"prompt":"How are the reportable segments defined? Specifically, why is X (the social media platform formerly known as Twitter) included in the AI segment rather than being its own segment? What is the CODM (chief operating decision maker) view and how are segment results presented? What unusual items affect the AI segment results, such as the Twitter/X impairment? {{spacex_s1}}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'How are the reportable segments defined? Specifically, why is X (the social media platform formerly known as Twitter) included in the AI segment rather than being its own segment? What is the CODM (chief operating decision maker) view and how are segment results presented? What unusual items affect the AI segment results, such as the Twitter/X impairment? {{spacex_s1}}'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Segment Reporting Analysis: SpaceX Post-xAI/X Merger\n\n## 1. How Reportable Segments Are Defined\n\nFollowing the xAI Merger (closed February 2, 2026) and the X Merger (closed March 28, 2025), collectively the "Mergers," SpaceX evaluated how to view and measure performance of the combined company. Effective **Q1 2026**, the Company realigned into **three operating and reportable segments**:\n\n| Segment | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Space** | Designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale (Falcon, Dragon, Starship) |\n| **Connectivity** | Operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by over 9,600 Starlink satellites in LEO, delivering connectivity to consumer, enterprise, and government customers across 164 markets (including Starlink Mobile) |\n| **AI** | Operates a "highly vertically integrated AI platform" spanning: (i) the frontier LLM **Grok**, (ii) AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, (iii) **X** — a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform, and (iv) AI computational infrastructure (e.g., the Colossus II facility in Memphis, Tennessee) |\n\nPrior-period presentations were conformed to this new structure (retrospective recasting).\n\n## 2. Why X Is Included in the AI Segment (Rather Than Standalone)\n\nSeveral factors explain the inclusion of X within AI rather than as its own segment:\n\n- **Strategic integration with the AI ecosystem.** The filing explicitly describes X as serving "as a foundational distribution and data engine for our AI ecosystem and further enhances Grok\'s truth-seeking objective." In other words, X is not being managed as a standalone social-media business but as a data and distribution layer feeding Grok and the broader AI platform.\n\n- **Common-control reorganization accounting.** The Mergers were accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control (Mr. Musk had a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X). xAI first acquired X in March 2025, and SpaceX then acquired xAI in February 2026. Because X was already integrated into xAI before being folded into SpaceX, the combined entity is being managed as a single vertically integrated AI business — compute infrastructure + frontier model (Grok) + consumer/enterprise AI solutions + real-time data/distribution platform (X).\n\n- **CODM\'s management view.** The CEO, as CODM, "organizes the Company, manages resource allocations, and measures performance" across only three segments. The CODM evidently does not view X as a discrete unit for which separate resource-allocation decisions are made; rather, X\'s advertising, subscription, and data-licensing revenues are managed alongside Grok subscriptions, API access, and AI compute infrastructure as part of one AI business.\n\n- **Revenue interrelationship.** The AI segment\'s revenue is described as coming from (i) advertising on X, (ii) premium subscriptions on X and Grok, (iii) data licensing, and (iv) API access to Grok models. These revenue streams are intertwined (e.g., Grok is distributed through X), reinforcing the CODM\'s view of a single integrated segment.\n\n## 3. The CODM View and Presentation of Segment Results\n\n**Who is the CODM:** The Company\'s Chief Executive Officer (Elon Musk) serves as the CODM.\n\n**Performance metric used by the CODM:**\n- The CODM "assesses performance and allocates resources to operating segments based on **segment income (loss) from operations**," by comparing actual results to (a) historical results and (b) previously forecasted financial information.\n- The filing notes the CODM "does not evaluate operating and reportable segments using" — the text is truncated, but the surrounding discussion of non-GAAP measures (Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA) indicates these non-GAAP measures are used by management for internal planning and forecasting, while the GAAP measure used by the CODM for segment reporting is segment income (loss) from operations.\n\n**How segment results are presented:**\n- Tables present **revenues, significant segment expenses, and income (loss) from operations** by reportable segment.\n- A reconciliation is provided from segment income (loss) from operations to **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** (defined as segment income/loss from operations excluding (i) depreciation and amortization, (ii) share-based compensation, (iii) restructuring charges, and (iv) impairment).\n- Selected segment financial highlights disclosed include, for example:\n  - **AI segment 2025:** Revenue $3,201 million; loss from operations $(6,355) million; Segment Adjusted EBITDA $(1,237) million\n  - **AI segment Q1 2026 capex:** $7,723 million (vs. Space $1,052 million and Connectivity $1,332 million), reflecting the heavy investment in AI compute infrastructure\n\n## 4. Unusual Items Affecting the AI Segment\n\nSeveral unusual or non-recurring items materially affect the AI segment\'s reported results:\n\n### a) Twitter Brand Impairment (2023)\n- A **one-time impairment of the Twitter brand intangible asset** was recorded when Twitter was rebranded to X in July 2023.\n- Impairment for the year ended December 31, 2024 **decreased by $3,775 million** compared to 2023, indicating the 2023 charge was approximately that magnitude — a very large item that distorts year-over-year comparisons.\n\n### b) AI Restructuring Charges (from October 2022 Twitter Acquisition)\n- Result from X Holdings\' October 2022 acquisition of Twitter.\n- Include:\n  - **Workforce restructuring** for former Twitter employees\n  - **Impairment and early termination penalties** from consolidation of Twitter\'s various office leases\n- For 2024 and 2023, the Company recorded **$36 million and $54 million**, respectively, of impairment related to leasehold improvements and office equipment as part of facilities consolidation efforts in the AI segment (classified within Restructuring charges, not Impairment, on the income statement).\n- Restructuring charges declined in 2024 because the bulk of the Twitter-acquisition restructuring occurred in 2023, partially offset by an increase in workforce-related restructuring charges.\n\n### c) Revenue Decline from Lost Advertising Partners (2024)\n- AI segment revenue for 2024 **decreased $341 million (11.5%)** vs. 2023, driven by a **$595 million decline in advertising revenue** due to the loss of advertising partners for X.\n- This was partially offset by a **$254 million increase in AI solutions and infrastructure revenue** (X subscriptions +$157 million; data licensing +$90 million).\n- In 2023 and 2024, "substantially all" AI segment revenue consisted of advertising, subscriptions, and data licensing generated from X.\n\n### d) EU Digital Services Act (DSA) Fine\n- In December 2025, the European Commission imposed a **€120 million fine** on XIUC, X, x.AI, and Elon Musk relating to alleged DSA breaches (deceptive blue checkmark, inadequate ad repository, insufficient researcher data access).\n- The parties challenged the decision in the General Court of the EU in February 2026; the challenge remains pending. This is a contingent/legal item affecting the AI segment.\n\n### e) Rising R&D and SG&A from Compute Investments\n- AI R&D is expected to increase (both absolutely and as a % of revenue) due to investments in compute infrastructure for Grok, including cloud computing, power generation, and depreciation of data center assets (processors, networking equipment).\n- AI SG&A may increase due to the **compute agreement with Cursor**.\n- Capitalized interest of **$169 million** in 2025 related to AI infrastructure data center construction (included in construction-in-progress).\n\n### f) Property, Plant & Equipment Impairments\n- The AI segment recorded impairments of leasehold improvements and office equipment in 2024 ($36M) and 2023 ($54M) tied to facilities consolidation — classified within Restructuring charges rather than Impairment on the income statement.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe post-merger SpaceX presents three segments (Space, Connectivity, AI) based on the CEO/CODM\'s management view. X is folded into the AI segment because, following the common-control reorganizations, it is managed as an integrated component of a vertically stacked AI platform — providing real-time data and distribution that feeds Grok — rather than as a standalone social-media business. The CODM evaluates segments using segment income (loss) from operations (with Segment Adjusted EBITDA used as a supplemental non-GAAP measure). The AI segment\'s results are heavily distorted by unusual items, most notably the ~$3.8 billion Twitter brand impairment in 2023, ongoing restructuring charges from the 2022 Twitter acquisition, a €120 million EU DSA fine, and significant revenue volatility from lost advertising partners — all of which investors should normalize for when assessing underlying operating performance.',
