        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What does the filing say about share-based compensation and how it is treated in Segment Adjusted EBITDA? Is share-based compensation a material expense? What are the amounts by segment? Does the filing caution about excluding share-based compensation from non-GAAP measures? {{spacex_s1}}'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Share-Based Compensation in the Filing\n\n## Treatment in Segment Adjusted EBITDA\n\nThe filing explicitly defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as segment income (loss) from operations **excluding** four items, the second of which is share-based compensation:\n\n> "Segment Adjusted EBITDA is defined as segment income (loss) from operations excluding (i) depreciation and amortization, **(ii) share-based compensation**, (iii) restructuring charges and (iv) impairment."\n\nThe same exclusion applies at the consolidated level: Adjusted EBITDA is defined as net income (loss) excluding (among other items) share-based compensation. In the reconciliation tables, share-based compensation is **added back** to segment income (loss) from operations to arrive at Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n## Materiality\n\nShare-based compensation is **highly material** and has grown dramatically. Consider its magnitude relative to Adjusted EBITDA:\n\n| Period | Total SBC | Adjusted EBITDA | SBC as % of Adj. EBITDA |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $639M | $1,127M | ~57% |\n| Q1 2025 | $232M | $1,730M | ~13% |\n| FY 2025 | $1,947M | $6,584M | ~30% |\n| FY 2024 | $784M | $5,350M | ~15% |\n| FY 2023 | $679M | $3,821M | ~18% |\n\nTotal SBC nearly **tripled** from FY 2024 ($784M) to FY 2025 ($1,947M), and Q1 2026 alone ($639M) already exceeds the full-year 2023 total. The filing also discloses that a portion of SBC is **capitalized** to the balance sheet ($60M in Q1 2026; $154M in FY 2025; $132M in FY 2024; $108M in FY 2023), meaning the total economic cost of equity compensation is even higher than the expensed amounts.\n\n## Amounts by Segment\n\n### Segment Adjusted EBITDA Reconciliation — Share-Based Compensation (in millions)\n\n| Period | Space | Connectivity | AI | Total Reportable Segments |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Q1 2026** | $145 | $116 | $378 | $639 |\n| **Q1 2025** | $108 | $75 | $49 | $232 |\n| **FY 2025** | $515 | $369 | $1,063 | $1,947 |\n| **FY 2024** | $472 | $296 | $16 | $784 |\n| **FY 2023** | $427 | $249 | $3 | $679 |\n\nKey observations:\n\n- **AI segment** SBC exploded from $3M (2023) → $16M (2024) → $1,063M (2025) → $378M in just Q1 2026 alone. This is by far the fastest-growing area, consistent with the segment\'s ramp-up and the "AI CEO Award" referenced in the filing.\n- **Space segment** SBC has been consistently the largest historically ($427M–$515M annually), reflecting its more mature workforce.\n- **Connectivity segment** SBC has grown steadily from $249M (2023) to $369M (2025).\n\n### SBC by Income Statement Line Item (in millions)\n\n| Line Item | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Cost of revenue | $76 | $39 | $253 | $193 | $167 |\n| Research & development | $362 | $75 | $859 | $230 | $179 |\n| Selling, general & administrative | $201 | $118 | $835 | $360 | $333 |\n| **Total** | **$639** | **$232** | **$1,947** | **$784** | **$679** |\n\nR&D saw the most dramatic increase — from $179M in 2023 to $859M in 2025 — reflecting the heavy equity-based incentives tied to engineering and product development, particularly in AI.\n\n## Cautions About Excluding Share-Based Compensation\n\nThe filing does **not** single out share-based compensation for a specific standalone caution, but it includes **broad cautionary language** about the limitations of Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA as non-GAAP measures, which by definition encompasses the SBC exclusion:\n\n> "Because of these limitations, Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for net income (loss), income (loss) from operations, or any other measure calculated in accordance with GAAP, and should be considered together with our GAAP financial measures and the reconciliations to the corresponding most directly comparable GAAP financial measures set forth."\n\nThe filing also warns about **comparability**:\n\n> "Other companies in our industry may calculate Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA differently than we do or may not calculate them at all, limiting their usefulness as comparative measures."\n\nAnd management explicitly acknowledges it "recognizes and considers the limitations of these measures."\n\n### Additional Context: SBC in Executive Compensation\n\nThe filing reveals that share-based compensation is deeply embedded in the company\'s executive incentive structure, which creates a circularity worth noting:\n\n- **CEO Awards** (SpaceX CEO Award and AI CEO Award): As of March 31, 2026, both performance milestones were considered **improbable**, and no SBC expense had been recognized. Once probable, expense will be recognized over the expected achievement period — meaning SBC could surge further if these milestones are achieved.\n- **CFO Award**: 4 million performance-based stock options were amended in January 2026 to vest based on **adjusted EBITDA** achievement ($10 billion thresholds during 2025–2029). Notably, the adjusted EBITDA used for this award **excludes share-based compensation** itself — meaning the very metric that determines the CFO\'s equity compensation is calculated by removing SBC as an expense. None of the options were earned based on 2025 performance.\n\nThis structural feature — where executive equity awards vest on a metric that excludes the cost of equity awards — is a notable aspect of the filing\'s disclosure, even though the company does not explicitly flag it as a caution.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=41.236,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
